	raw-html:<ul><li>Software is an abstraction over hardware, and the invention of the <i>stored-program</i> computer by Babbage is the crucial enabling idea.<li>Digital hardware (based on zeros and ones) is not a law of nature, but an abstraction over the physics of transistors, and requires engineering effort to make it work.<li>There are several levels of abstraction <em>within</em> the software level and <em>within</em> the hardware level.<li>All data in a computer are represented as bitstreams (binary sequences). The same bitstream may represent different values depending on the context in which it appears.</ul>
        
h3: Computational Thinking Practices P1, P2, P3, P4, P5
	raw-html: <div class="todo"><strong>Paul</strong>, I drafted this, can you take a quick look and, when you deem it ready, please remove this comment? --MF, 11/23/17</div>
	raw-html: <p>Students learn about the <strong>abstraction (P3)</strong> hierarchy of computers of as three overarching domains: the software domain (with its own four layers of programmatic abstraction), the digital domain (which includes four levels of conceptual abstraction), and the analog domain. As they do, students <strong>analyze artifacts (P2)</strong> of this technology, for example, by learning programming libraries, system kernels, machine language, and circuitry. Although this unit has fewer programming projects than some of the earlier units, students do <strong>create artifacts (P2)</strong> such as a computer hardware quiz app, and a project of their own choice focused around a new block from one of the Snap<em>!</em> libraries. Students <strong>communicate (P5)</strong> as they work to understand these new ideas, for example, by listing application programs they use, teaching a new Snap<em>!</em> procedure to other students, and discussing the classification of a "computer."</p><p>Students <strong>connect computing (P1)</strong> as they wrap up the year of AP content reviewing and learning more about many of the global impacts of computing, including impacts on human communication and collaboration; social engagement in tasks too complex for an single institution's computers or for computers at all; various innovations including machine learning, data mining, modeling, and simulation; Mooreâ€™s Law; intellectual property; and some of the difficult issues in technology such as conflict minerals and addressing the digital divide.</p>

